  "prompt": "Does four wheel drive consume more fuel than two wheel drive?",
  "response": "Yes, generally speaking, four-wheel drive (4WD) systems consume more fuel than two-wheel drive (2WD) systems. This increase in fuel consumption can be attributed to several factors:\n\n1. **Additional Weight:** 4WD vehicles tend to be heavier because they have extra components like a transfer case, additional drive shafts, and differentials for the front and rear axles.\n\n2. **Increased Drivetrain Losses:** With more components involved in transmitting power to all four wheels, there are additional energy losses in the drivetrain, which can reduce fuel efficiency.\n\n3. **Tire Resistance:** In 4WD mode, especially if the vehicle is equipped with all-terrain tires, there may be increased rolling resistance, which can also lead to higher fuel consumption.\n\n4. **Operational Mode:** In vehicles with selectable 4WD systems, if 4WD is engaged while driving on dry, paved roads, it can lead to unnecessary fuel consumption because the system is designed for low-traction scenarios.\n\nIn contrast, 2WD vehicles are typically lighter and have fewer components, which can lead to better fuel efficiency under normal driving conditions. However, the actual difference in fuel consumption can vary depending on the specific vehicle and driving conditions.",
